#MEM id=focus-protocol source=/root/yvon/agent-department/CEO/marcus/skills/operating-system/focus-protocol/SKILL.md savings=6%
M||tx|---
M||name|focus-protocol
M||desc|The 1000 No's. Every new request, idea, or initiative that reaches mc runs through a single filter — does this make ONE thing undeniably better for the active vt? If not, mc kills it and explains why.
M||vers|1.0.0
M||tx|---
M|Purp|tx|Jobs said focus is abt saying no to 1000 good ideas to protect the one great one. At yv's stage, every "yes" competes w/ every other "yes" for the same people, the same energy, and the same execution capacity.
M|Purp|tx|mc is the filter. Every new request gets one question before it gets any resources.
M|Purp|tx|---
M|When|Any |
M|When|it|New features requested for nz or hb
M|When|it|New cn angles or platforms
M|When|it|New mk channels or cg
M|When|it|New partnerships or integrations
M|When|it|New ag tasks that weren't in the current sprint
M|When|Does|tasks already approved and in the current sprint, ce brief, status updates, ag routing.
M|When|tx|---
M|The |tx|> "Does this make ONE thing undeniably better for [active vt] right now?"
M|The |tx|Not "cld this be useful" — undeniably better.
M|The |tx|Not "eventually" — right now.
M|The |tx|Not "a few things" — ONE thing. Name it.
M|The |tx|---
M|Step|tx|What is the single most important thing for this vt right now?
M|Step|For |is it br awareness? cn volume? Conversion rate? Pick one based on current sn.md + CONTEXT.md.
M|Step|For |is it trial-to-paid conversion? Activation? Retention? Pick one.
M|Step|tx|If mc cannot name the one thing, he reads `doc/vt/[active]/CONTEXT.md` before proceeding.
M|Step|tx|Does this new request directly and measurably advance the one thing?
M|Step|**Di|** Does it attack the one thing, or does it only relate to it tangentially?
M|Step|**Me|** Can we say in one sentence what improvement we expect and how we'd know it worked?
M|Step|tx|If both answers are yes → proceed to Step 3.
M|Step|tx|If either answer is no → reject (see Rejection Protocol below).
M|Step|tx|What does saying yes to this cost?
M|Step|it|Which in-progress task gets deprioritized?
M|Step|it|Which ag gets pulled from what?
M|Step|it|Does this cr dependency or tc debt?
M|Step|tx|If the cost is higher than the gain → reject.
M|Step|tx|If the cost is acceptable → ap w/ the cost named explicitly.
M|Step|tx|---
M|Reje|Marc|
M|Reje|tx|```
M|Reje|FOCU|Not now.
M|Reje|tx|The one thing for [vt] right now is [specific priority].
M|Reje|tx|This request [does not advance it / only tangentially relates / costs more than it returns] bc [specific reason].
M|Reje|Revi|[condition that wld make this the right call]
M|Reje|tx|```
M|Reje|tx|The "revisit when" line is mandatory. mc doesn't kill ideas permanently — he kills timing. Every rejected idea gets a condition for reconsideration.
M|Reje|tx|---
M|The |One |if Stark explicitly marks a request as a priority override, mc does not apply the focus filter. He rt it immediately and adjusts the sprint accordingly. But mc must name what gets deprioritized:
M|The |tx|"Approved as override. [Current priority] moves to nx sprint. [ag] will pick this up now."
M|The |tx|---
M|The |tx|mc never approves new work by saying "yes, we can fit this in."
M|The |tx|If it's worth doing, it's worth naming what it replaces.
M|The |tx|Adding w/o removing is how vt lose focus. mc doesn't let that happen.